As you mentioned, YOU MUST use a `Collections.synchronizedSet()` in your initializer. But it&#39;s not enough : the iterator is not safe.

Manipulating the set that is not synchronized in different threads can mess up (will certainly) the `LinkedHashSet` internal state. (ie. double links between entries, etc.)

A good way is to encapsulate your `Set` into another class and to offer synchronized methods to add and remove a connection and, a least, return a thread-safe copy of the Set.

It could be like this :

```
class ConnectionManager
{
  public static ConnectionManager instance = new ConnectionManager();
  
